07193nam a22010455i 9781501744556DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191997nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017445567 a10.7591/97815017445562doi  a(DE-B1597)534237  a(OCoLC)1129184120  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD6976.T24bK37 1996eb 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a331/.04138422200aTelecommunications :bRestructuring Work and Employment Relations Worldwide /ced. by Harry C. Katz. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b8 charts/graphs, 49 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell International Industrial and Labor Relations Reports00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction and Comparative Overview -- tPart 1. Technology and Market-Driven Restructuring -- tChapter 1. United States -- tChapter 2. United Kingdom -- tChapter 3. Australia -- tChapter 4. Canada -- tPart 2. Labor-Mediated Restructuring -- tChapter 5. Germany -- tChapter 6. Japan -- tChapter 7. Norway -- tChapter 8. Italy -- tPart 3. State-Led Growth and Modernization -- tChapter 9. Mexico -- tChapter 10. Korea -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTelecommunications provides the first comparative description of a pivotal service industry in which deregulation, privatization, and globalization have shaped corporate strategies and structure, and altered the nature of work. A chapter is devoted to each of the countries discussed: the United States, England, Canada, Australia, Japan, Germany, Italy, Norway, Mexico, and Korea. To facilitate comparisons, the authors use a common framework in analyzing changes and their implications for work and employment relations. Most employees in telecommunications, both white-collar and blue-collar, are unionized, and that has highlighted the tension between downsizing and participatory employment strategies. The authors describe adjustment paths adopted in the Anglo-Saxon countries which emphasize a technology- and market-driven approach, in contrast to Japan and several European countries where labor and social pressures have mediated the course and consequences of industrial adjustment. The strategic approach in Korea and Mexico is again different, relying on the state to set the pace and terms of change. The United States and United Kingdom have emerged as pattern leaders in the international telecommunications industry through their aggressive deregulation and restructuring. While downsizing has devastated employee morale, experiments in alternative solutions based on union and employee participation are simultaneously underway.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIndustrial relationsvCase studies. 0aTelecommunicationxEconomic aspects. 0aTelecommunicationxEmployees. 4aLabor History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aBamber, Greg J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatt, Rosemary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaykowski, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz Guzman, Jose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarbishire, Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspinosa, Alejandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerner, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarza, Enrique de la, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilman, Mark, econ